If it doesn"t light up Rotate it AND DO IT WITH URGENCY! I bought these to replace the cargo lights outside a chevy pickup for more light.. There was corrosion on the OEM contacts after 10yrs. So i had to destroy a perfectly good bulb and remove it in pieces.
 Next step...install the LED...No light...hmm what's that smell?? Oh!..its the new bulb! Oh Crap..its stuck in the connector and won't come out!!
No one bothered to mention that IF you install these backwards that they WILL melt in a matter of seconds and can probably burst into flame. Hmmm, it would have been good to know that.
  Had to jump out of the slick truck bed in the rain and scurry around to the dash controls to shut it off in a hurry! Good for an adrenaline rush.
  So with the 2nd of the 2 bulbs I gently touched it to the connector to verify proper polarity BEFORE fully plugging it into the socket.
Once installed correctly I had to modify the wires to make a good connection. But its working now and it IS BRIGHT!
So i have one white bright LED cargo light and one dim yellowish OEM cargo light.
  I would highly recommend replacing your bulbs one at a a time and verify the proper polarity on each one. Just doing a blanket install on multiples amd then turning on the switch and expecting to replace the ones that are in backwards could create a serious hazard.
summary: BEWARE: If installed backwards bulb can melt and burst into flame in about 30 seconds! Other than that, its alright.

I bought mine after 2 Accurate Tool inverters went dead. The 1500watt PSW went dead in a little over one month. The 2000 only lasted about 18 days. Both bought on the "auction" website...E-you know what...so both were beyond the return date. Pffffft....
  Well, I have had the Tiger Claw, or (FU JOW) in Chinese, for 3 weeks. I use two 100ah batteries, with 2/0 cable, with my 850watt power consumption microwave (600watt output),...and the cables only get just noticeably a TAD warm, by the 200 amp ANL fuse I have. I don't plan on running anything more than 1000 watts...if that. It is quite a drain on the batteries. If you have the capacity, this should run just about anything up to 1300 watts pretty well...assuming you have thick cables, and plenty of JUICE!!!!!!

I have had no trouble with the unit at all. There is a new version out, where CFL bulbs don't flicker. My CFL bulbs do not flicker. So, next generation...There was also a Fan issue, when they power up, they would be weak and click. I connected a .01 micro farad ceramic disk capacitor to the negative terminal, and the case ground. (it does not matter which wire goes to the negative terminal)... The fans power up just fine. Youtube is great for information!!
  When running the microwave the fans kick on after about 2 minutes, otherwise for a 300 watt 1 cup coffee maker, it is silent.
  This is the best price for a 1500watt PSW inverter, even on the "auction" website. The Accurate Tools Inverters were cheap...but did not last...they were over voltaged at 125volts. The Tiger Claw reads 114.9, or so...which drops a bit to 111.9 or so when powering something.
  My application is a Solar Generator, still working on getting the panels up and running, but I have the batteries in a roll-able box, with the inverter mounted on the front. The Microwave can sit on top. I can put it in my car, or roll around to where I need it in the house. And eventually will charge it with the Sun.
  I have read where people have used them for 15 months or more, and so, it seemed reliable, and that is why I got one. The unit is solid, and seems well built, but there are no voltage/wattage meters, nor is there a USB port.  I hope my unit continues to do well.
  So far, I like it allot.

Ironically, the 4-pin plug on this which is made to go into the vehicle's 4-pin plug had rubber shielding around the metal terminals to create a seal.  I installed this on an '03 F150 which also had said shielding.  The two won't work together, only one end is to have this shielding or "boot."  But fear not as the fix is easy: I just took a utility knife and cut the rubber off the plug on this Hopkins unit.  It then plugged into the truck fine.

Otherwise, these are not of the most robust construction.  Hopkins also sells a more heavy duty adapter under the "Endurance" line which is of better construction.  I've used both and will opt for the Endurance in the future.  The Endurance is gray in color and has a raised "X" on the 7-pin cover.
summary: Does the job but cheap plastic

reviewText: Not a good charger for AGM or Gel batteries. Like so many other reviewers have found, charging voltages are excessive and erratic. Every time this thing was hooked up to a bank of AGM deep cycle batteries voltage spiked to 15 plus volts with jumps to as high as 17 volts. Brand new batteries don't need reconditioning and I'll choose that option myself if I want it. Finally bought a Ctek, which is charging at the exact  specified voltages required for my batteries ,and is right on the money when checked with a voltmeter. I wouldn't feel right even giving this thing away. I've been burned twice by Schumacher, and I'll be spending a little more from now on to get a higher quality charger like the CTEK  or BatteryMinder.
summary: Not a good charger for AGM or Gel batteries

reviewText: I decided to do a test of Griot's Garage Brilliant Finish Car Wash compared with Meguiar's G7164 Gold Class Car Wash Shampoo & Conditioner - 64 oz.. I tried to repeat the same procedure in each case. Each says to use 1 oz of the car wash liquid to one gallon of water. For each one I used a tablespoon to measure the car wash, placed it into my car wash bucket, then added the same amount of hot water from the faucet. Each produced about the same amount of suds. The results are in my last paragraph if you want to skip ahead. The Griot's Garage container states: Brilliant Finish Car Wash is made from premium ingredients to ensure you maintain paint care perfection, bucket after bucket. Its thick, concentrated formula makes tons of suds, produces a streak-free finish, is pH balanced (which prevents wax stripping), safe on all exterior finishes, and is biodegradable. The Meguiar's Gold Class container states: Meguiar's Gold Class Car Wash Shampoo and Conditioner is a rich and luxurious product designed to both wash and condition paint in one easy step. The premium formula gently foams away {when I recorded this with Dragon Naturally Speaking v13, it thought I said "bombs away"} tough dirt, road grime and contaminants without compromising wax protection. Ultrarich paint conditioners clear away debris to reveal color and clarity, leaving paint looking radiant. The Gold Class Collection blends the finest conditioners and premium ingredients to deliver exceptional results. The detergent is biodegradable. I washed one side of my car with the Griot's and the other side with Meguiar's. The end result was that it was pretty much a toss up. They are both good products. The Meguiar's suds may have lasted a bit longer but that is just subjective. I was quite satisfied with both products and I can't say that one performed really better than the other. So it is just a matter of personal preference and possibly whether you plan to use other products by Griot's or Meguiar's. You might also have a preference to the smell. The Griot's has kind of a watermelon scent and the Meguiar's has a rich shampoo type scent that I prefer more. Also, I can say that based upon Amazon's current prices, the 64 oz Griot's is $12.99 and the 64 oz Meguiar's is $8.49, so the Griot's cost is about 50 percent more. Thinking of it in terms of making a gallon of car wash, the cost difference is negligible as the cost of the Griot's is $0.20 per gallon and the Meguiar's is $0.13 per gallon. So take your pick. And to speed up the process of drying your car, I recommend the The Original California Car Duster 20114 Dry Jelly Blade (Colors may vary).
summary: Griot's Garage Brilliant Finish Car Wash vs Meguiar's Gold Class Car Wash Shampoo and Conditioner

These lug nuts look good on my RAM 1500, but not quite as nice as the OEM lug nuts which have a smooth and flat top.

The lifetime part of the warranty is restricted to rusting and not damage due to repetitive removal and installation of the lug nuts which I misunderstood. Repeated removal and reinstallation cause damage to the outer shell that makes it near impossible to remove in an emergency situation with the vehicle manufacturers lug wrench.

I would love to see someone make a decorative lug nut that is solid metal so that they will stand up to the repeated tire rotation and changing of wheels. These lug nuts, as with all decorative lug nuts, are of a two-piece design with a decorative shell covering the working part of the lug. When this happens, I will be first in line.
summary: Okay, but not for a lifetime.

Great cap, after all it's a Stant.  I would recommend you check for the correct part number on the Stant website.  For my '68 Cougar the Amazon part search and the Stant page came up with different part numbers and the Stant number matched my worn out Stant that fits.  I'm not sure if the Amazon part number cap would have worked or not.

Update:
A short time after installing this gas cap I began to notice gas fumes while I was working in my trunk.  I was concerned that I may not have good connections on my filler pipe but I eventually traced the source of fumes to the rubber gasket on this locking gas cap.  It doesn't fit the filler tightly.  I replaced the cap with the standard, non-locking Stant OE type gas cap for my car and it works perfectly - no more fumes escaping.  I've downgraded the locking cap from 5 to 3 stars.  I'm tempted to give it 2 stars but Stant generally makes very high quality stuff and I'm not entirely sure why this cap didn't fit well.

I purchased this pump in 2008 and it's still going strong. Yes, it's cheaply made and has some silly design elements, but I paid about twenty bucks and it has paid for itself in emergency use.

Silly design elements first: the flash light is merely OK, but a light would have been more useful had it illuminated the gauge. Plus, the illumination that the light provides is only good for close up work (but not detailed work). Second, the gauge is difficult to read, even in the light, with my sixty-five year old eyes. I have to 'guesstimate' 33 PSI, which my current vehicle requires.

However, on the plus side I can reach all four tires on my 2014 Outlander as long as I switch doors for each side of the vehicle. And it may take a long time to inflate from, say, 28 to 33 PSI (over five minutes), it is a big help when I am nowhere near a real compressor. Therein lies the value - I can top off my tires anytime the 'Low Tire Pressure' light comes on. That happens about twice a year for me since we experience some sharp weather changes in my region about that frequently. To be honest, I try to maintain optimum pressure by checking my levels monthly and resolving any condition at a local gas station before it becomes a problem. But when the temperature drops from the 70s to the 30s like it sometimes does the pressure drops accordingly.

Since 2008 I've probably used this thirty times. It costs a buck to use the gas station air pump, and I paid about twenty bucks for this at a big box store. Plus, it's still operational, so I have more than gotten my money's worth from it.

This is not the best quality pump and it has some flaws, but when you need one - you need one! I find it reassuring that it's always handy in my vehicle.
summary: Consumer quality, but does the job

This is a high-quality belt [period]  I've tried others that had touted the durability of their product and way cool better-than-other's specs, but these so called "better than" belts all fell short of my expectations...uh...obviously.  <g>
Let's face it, most Chinese scooters use the same basic models, they just package them differently. My scooter's basic models Nos. are any one of these:  ZN150T-120, BN157QMJ, or, GY6B (second generation). It has taken several brand names in the US too. All of them, or I should say mine, is ~150cc . This PL20707 fits these engines perfectly and I believe the extra one I ordered with the one in use is still on the shelf somewhere.  Cross-reference your original part number and manufacturer (visually, if possible) on your existing scooter with a chart one will find, let say, at a good solid American-Made Manufacturer's website. I can see you thinking, "All this for a frackin' belt!?!"  <g><g>

If you find quality you stick with it, moreover, if you find quality and it's American-made, you support it.  Very quick delivery too!

EDIT:  As I sit here eating crow, I've found out that the Gates Powerlink belt is NOT American made, it is made in China. My apologies and a little more humble pie, if you please?
summary: You Can Spend More For Inferior belts, but why?

This was the strongest best looking receiver on Amazon for my 1999 Chrysler Town & Country minivan.  It calls for you to drill two holes into the frame of the vehicle and then fish wire the bolts through an opening in the frame that is about two feet away from the drilled holes.  To my amazement the fishing wire that was included actually worked.  That is of course after I filed the round bolt heads into ovals in order to fit them through the frame opening.  And, after I got the first bolt routed through the frame I found out that the nuts included were the wrong size and would not work.  After a 20 minute excursion to my local hardware store (with the other bolt in hand), I was back at it filing down the second bolt head so it would fit through the frame opening.  So even with the extra filing and trip to the hardware store, I got it installed by myself and it looks good and sturdy and should function well.
summary: Strong well built tow hitch receiver, with the WRONG nuts & bolts included.

After using Barrier Reef Wash & Wax, and being very impressed, I had high expectations for this spray wax. Sadly this spray wax wasn't what I had hoped for.

1: Even if you might like this product, the sprayer is terrible. As soon as you squeeze it the first time, you start to worry that it it break before you get done. It doesn't spray evenly and sometimes doesn't spray at all. So the point being, even if you like this spray, if you can't apply it, then it becomes useless.
2: The wax doesn't come off as easily as other spray waxes. If I have to work hard, I'd rather go old school and use a paste wax and get the real thing.
3: Don't get any over spray on the windows or black trim. it will smear when you try to get it off.
4: It will make your car shiny, but it is a very superficial glassy shine, not the deep glossy shine I had hoped for.
5: The wax/shine won't last long at all, one wash and it's gone.
summary: Even if you might like this product

I have several VIAIR pumps. Unfortunately the last one was stolen. I believe this one will be my favorite for the following reasons. Number one is the auto shut off. Many units require that you return to the pumps to shut it off. In the past I would over fill the tire, return to the pump, shut it off and then return to the tire and reduce air to the proper pressure. Doable but extra effort. Number two is the continuous run cycle. Many units can run for 15 minutes then require a 30 minute cool down time. While maybe not important to some why risk it and have the auto thermal protection shut it down and wait 30 minutes. As an added bonus I suspect to get the continues run time the rpms on the motor have been reduced and the unit is pretty quiet. Number three the supplied air gun has a bleed off button which allows you to reduce air pressure easily if you over fill. Number four the unit comes with two hoses, the extension for dully tires and the air gun with gage so you are ready for most anything. Number five the whole package is small enough to fit under most SUV's back seat. reviewText:
All boaters who have 2- or 4-stroke marine engines need to have a fuel additive in there gas to protect against ethanol effects.  I have used StaBil products for years; I add to all gas used on the boat during the boating season.  In addition, I use Sea Foam before putting the boat in winter storage to clean up the combustion chambers on my 2-stroke 90 hp outboard.  This is especially important because the oil rich gas entering the engine can leave carbon deposits on the cyclinder heads and walls.

At the end of the season I add Sea Foam directly to the carburator throat 3-5 times while the engine is running (just enough to have white smoke coming out the exhaust but not enough to stall the engine).  Finally, I add another shot to stall the engine and shut it off.  I wait 24 hours and then restart the engine and run until all white smoke is gone.  If the engine runs rough that is to be expected.  I then perform normal winterization activities before storing..

BTW, I use Sea Foam in the same way in my garden tractor and lawn mowers.  The garden tractor is 1989 Cub cadet and is still going strong.  Recently, I started adding Sea Foam to the gas in my 1997 Ford 150 truck; once every other month.  So far...so good!
summary: Sea Foam Motor Treatment for Outboard Engines

I'm a rookie and this book helps me work on my new (to me) Jeep, but it could be better.  Since the book covers nearly 40 years, there have been a lot of minor variations.  For example, there are a half dozen different transmissions.  I hoped the book would do a better job of helping me determine what transmission I have, but it doesn't.  Since my Jeep is a 3-speed built in '74, it helped me narrow down the possibilities.  HOWEVER, that is assuming the trans is original and hasn't been replaced with a newer year.
Also you will need a good understanding of working on cars to fully utilize this book.  Some of procedures list several steps and give the order to remove certain parts.  It's very good information, unless you are uncertain on what each part is.  For example, I thought the little "widget" part between the battery and the starter was bad.  I wanted to test/replace it but I didn't know what it was called.  After much searching I ended up finding it listed in the electrical section and the widget was a starter solenoid.  I was surprised the solenoid wasn't detailed in the beginning of the book with a picture of the engine bay.
summary: Good information but it could be better

Want to re-initialize your tire pressure monitor sensors when you rotate your tires?  Changing a TPM sensor?  With this tool you can do it in a few seconds.

Some older TPM sensors are re-initialized with permanent magnets.  If you don't have this tool but have the newer TPM sensors, you can do it by adding or releasing air until the TPM sensor sends a signal to your car (check your owner's manual or shop manual).  But having one of these handy for the tire people when you have anythign done with your tires or wheels makes everything simple and accurate, and you can do it yourself in a few minutes to fix the problem when your car is indicating pressures on the wrong wheels.  This this tool is a convenience, not a necessity, but it is a huge convenience.
summary: Makes Re-Initializing Late-Model Tire Pressure Monitors a Snap

reviewText: The best thing to keep your face warm. The only problem it when you breath your breath is sent into your eyes.

The way this tool works is you put the arm of the tool in the down position, and then put the tool midway on the belt between two pulleys.  Then push on the tool until you feel the click.  Once you feel the click, you stop pushing tension on the belt with your finger and then look at the resulting measurement.  The top of the moving arm (left of the picture in this product description) intersects with the scale of numbers engraved on the tool.  Wherever that intersection point lies is the resulting belt tension number.  I can tell the tool basically converts some level of belt deflection into a corresponding tension number.  By applying the specified amount of tension (i.e. up to the point of the clicking noise of the tool), the belt has deflected a certain amount and the moving arm will only move up as much as the belt has deflected.  So I would say the key aspect to this tool is when the clicking happens which assures when the appropriate amount of deflection has been applied and then to read the measurement thereafter.  Very cool tool.

The only possible ways I can see a wrong measurement occuring is if the user applies more force to the belt (after the clicking already  happened) or if the clicking mechanism is out of calibration and clicks too early or too late (thereby applying too little or too much force to the belt to create a wrong measurement).  I can't imagine the clicking being out of calibration as it looks like a very simple mechanism.  So I would say this tool is very accurate almost all the time.  I took a few readings of my belt and always got fairly consistent readings, maybe differing by plus/minus 10 lbs.

I read in some forums where people would say they had no room to insert this tool, but the tool is only 5 inches long (shorter than most pens) and for the most part, if you have room to put your finger on a belt and be able to push on it, you will most likely be able to fit this tool there too.  The tool has a rubber strap for your finger to help prevent you from dropping it while finding your way to the belt.  Since it's so small, I might recommend you have one of those telescopic magnetic pick-up tools handy in case you drop it down in the engine compartment somewhere since the tool is that small (however, the only magnetic part of the krikit I got is on the pen clip).

You should also be aware that the krikit model 91132 has a tension measurement range of 100-320 lbs while model 91107 has a lower range (30-160 lbs).  My car ('03 G35) requires a new belt tension of greater than 200 lbs on one of the belts, so I got the 91132.

I also wanted to comment on the other amazon user reviewer who mentioned the gauge was ineffective for him.  I would have to say he likely has loose belts because the tool, in my opinion, is highly accurate if used correctly and it's kind of hard to use it incorrectly.  But even with loose belts, you might never notice any noticeable squeeling...basically you can be lucky and never see a problem until the next belt change.

I tried to cover as much as I can because I could never find anyone giving a detailed review of this product which would have helped me evaluate this product prior to buying it, but now that I have it and actually used it, I think it's a very handy gauge and anyone who needs to manually adjust their belt tension should get one.  I know some people can tension their belts by feel or using some belt twisting rule of thumb, and that's how I used to do it too, but I get much peace of minding know that my belt is tensioned EXACTLY to specs.
summary: No need for more expensive gauges.

I am impressed with the overall design and composition of the light.  The lens and housing are lightweight yet durable and made really well considering the weight of materials used.  Possesses a good quality bulb socket and switch as well.

Although the light can be used for exterior applications, please note: the light fixture is not watertight.  The back panel is thin gauge sheet metal and has mounting holes drilled through it, the sheet metal is recessed ever so slightly into the fixture housing.  This allows the housing to mount tight against most surfaces.  There is a water 'seepage slot' cut into the bottom most portion of the housing if some water were to gain access into the light fixture from above.  The manner in which the clear lens snaps into the white, outer housing seems that it would readily shed water and prevent entrance in this region.

This is to ABS what the other Code Scan tools are for your engine. It gives you historical codes and current codes so you can get a good over all picture of whats happening. You must have a basic understanding of ABS and the Sensors / Components that make up the system. If you do then this is the tool that will save you a fortune by not having to take your vehicle to a dealer! If you have no idea of how ABS works, keep taking your car to the dealer or learn fast so you can save! Only possible complaint some may have is that the tool will not reset the ABS light like you can with the Check Engine light with the other scan tools. Me personally, I want to see the historical codes so that I can ascertain if a problem is intermittant or not. Once you repair what is wrong your lignt will go out anyway. Most ABS computers reset themselves each time you start your car. The Light comes on for a reason!

Did my first oil change with it.  Small car... Fiat Abarth.  too low to even drive up ramps.  Haven't had it that long but I figured I'd always have it changed at the dealer for convenience.  Its not convenient to drive somewhere and sit for an hour though..

Stuck this down the dipstick tube and a few minutes later it was sucking air.  I stuck it in another 1/4 inch and it sucked out another half quart or so.
Filled the crank case with exactly what was prescribed by the manual (4 qt) and it came right to the top line perfectly.  Started the car and ran it for a few seconds, checked again, no black streaks... pure amber.  It got all the oil out (maybe even more than the drain plug?).

The hose is very heat sensitive.  The larger diameter hose collapsed almost completely with warm oil and under a vacuum.  When it was done and cooled... it maintained that shape.  It never stopped sucking though.

For those that don't understand that "don't shove it too far in" instructions... 2 things.  first, the dipstick is supposed to be at the deepest part of the pan.  2nd.  If it curves around, it can get caught on the bottom of the dipstick tube (not polished smooth) and just shear off, leaving hose in your oil pan.  If it feels snagged... don't pull.  try to push , twist and gently wiggle it back out.. and don't do that again.
summary: Like a charm.  but be careful not to over insert.

After using this product, I immediately regret all the previous instances when I used chain oil instead of this wax spray. It works just as well, if not better than oil, but without that obnoxious splatter you get on the first few rides after greasing the chain. It repels water better, so I can go longer without having to reapply the product. Personally, I can ride 500-600 miles in urban areas, and the chain still looks usable--though my preference is to re-grease every 500-600 miles, regardless.

The price seems a bit steep, but I enjoy the quality so much, I feel it's worth the investment (between $12-$15, is what I've seen). If the price tag still bothers you, I suggest shopping around until you find a price you can live with, so long as you give it try.
summary: No Obnoxious Oil to Deal With

Before this on my previous 2 Nissan trucks (1993 and 1998) I had the 1200 model, and the now extinct 1100 model on my 1996 Honda. Same problems as everyone else... water buildup, reflector corrosion, even I took the housings apart and used clear silicone to seal them back up... i guess I learned my lesson. This model actually appeared to be the best built of the bunch, but I was young and stupid at the time, and had blind faith. Now I'm replacing them with Hella FF 50 lights, which are supposed to be part of the MAINSTREAM Hella line. Another brand that is discontinued in the US but VERY durable is CATZ. I have those on my 2001 Subaru for three years and the only problem I have is exterior housing wear...as it should be.

UPDATE:  Took off these lights from the front air dam.
BEHOLD!!! (see pics) Witness the incredible longevity and prowess of these lights.  According to city locals, rumor has it that trash pickup day was scheduled for the following morning. Tragically, these light housings were never seen or heard from ever since.  If you happen to witness any Hella Optilux light housing, functional or not, then don't walk, RUN, as fast as you can in the opposite direction.  You have been warned.

There is super bright and then there are these bulbs! I had to drive at night a lot mainly due to the heat in the constant sun throughout the day and these bulbs brighten everything like its mid day in the middle of the night. They turn pitch black darkness in the forest into a pleasant drive. The best part is how well I could see the animals on the road and managed to avoid so many accidents! reviewText:
I purchased a BOLT Jeep Wrangler hood lock for added security.  The BOLT system comes with four 1/4 stainless steel rivets that needs a powerful riveter to install.  After researching the reviews, I felt confident that this tool would be able to handle the job, and the price is perfect for a tool that is not often used.  I am pleased to say that this tool comes with very good and easy to understand instructions.  The only thing that threw me a bit off was the size markings, which are not in fractions (1/4), but in decimals.  The instructions convert this for you on a chart.

Without going into much detail, it worked very well.  You will need to have some significant arm strength for 1/4 SS rivets, but the tool powered through it.  I used an Auto Zone riveter once for a project a couple of years ago, and it broke on the first rivet.  This is a sturdy tool, and is now another option for future projects that I would not have considered otherwise.

I drive to work on I-95 and rocks and debris are constantly kicked up. I bought my 2015 Subaru Forester 2.5i Premium and wanted to avoid as many dings as possible. These work great and look good on my Subie.

A few notes on the installation. The "pins" are pretty easy to insert and pull out once you get a feel for them. The rear guards install in about 5 mins. You simply ADD them to the molding and put in some pins and screws. The front guards take a little more time because you must REPLACE the factory moldings with the splash guard moldings. The hardest part of the install for me was removing the factory moldings. Make sure you OPEN the doors! Also, a couple of pins did not come out for me initially. I had to use a pair of needle nose pliers to remove them after I removed the factory moldings. But not a big deal at all. Once the factory moldings were off, it was easy to put in the splash guard moldings. I recommend spending about 5 mins studying the instructions (from the Subaru Tech website), and then going for the install. The whole process took me about 30 mins.
summary: Improved Look with Protection From Rocks and Debris

reviewText:
These horns were an easy install on a 2004 Hyundai Accent GT Hatchback. My car had one horn of the same type, so it was just a matter of a swap out for one horn, and some simple splicing of wires to add the second horn to the circuit. (You may need additional relays or fuses if you have a different set up in your car, and the included instructions will diagram different installation options)

The horns are rated at 118 Db, and I don't have  the equipment to comment on whether they reach that, but I can honestly say that the horn is startling loud even from inside the car.

My previous horn had a wimpy sound like the roadrunner's iconic "Meep Meep", but now, it is a jarring, cacophonous, dissonant blast, which reminds me of a locomotive. The German description on the box is TRAFFIKBLASTER. An apt description.

The horns are designed in Germany, and manufactured in India. I found the build quality to be high. They are heavy in the hand, and the connections were strong and well mounted to the frame. A huge step up from the Korean made horn I replaced.

These fit on 2002 Jeep grand Cherokee.  Takes some patience and muscle to get the old ones out and these in but saved huge $ by doing it myself.  These are a recent new design where the dust boot is recessed into the joint and it will poof out some after you fill with grease.  Also the grease zerks are not the kind that you pop the end of your grease gun onto.  They are now small little ones that require a needle end to fill them and they are right at the edge of the ball joint, not in the middle.  Lincoln part 5803 or similar will work to get grease in them. The picture you see may not be exactly what you get as at the time of this review, the picture is still showing the older design.  One thing I did not like about these is there is not a good flat shoulder to press them in from the bottom.  It's more of a rolled lip and the ball joint kept wanting to get cockeyed and tilt a little bit into one side of the installer tube when trying to press it in.  Got it done but poor design in that area made it WAY harder than it should have been
summary: These fit on 2002 Jeep grand Cherokee.  Takes some patience and muscle to get the old ones out and these in.

The SpeedoDRD model S1 fits the 2014 Suzuki Vstrom DL650A ABS model (and other models; check their web site on http://12oclocklabs.com/).  On the 2014 Suzuki Vstrom DL650A ABS, the speedometer sensor is a black connector located on the left side of the motorcycle.  The 3 wire connector is at the V section of the frame on the left side.  Lift the tab up on the connector and pull it open.  The SpeedoDRD connector bridges the original connector.  The controller is very small and I tucked mine under the seat in front of the ECU.  It is held in place by the battery strap (just as the ECU is).  The controller is accessible by removing the seat.  The installation looks very stock;  no one will even notice this is there.  My speedometer was off by 7% (checked with a GPS) and the SpeedoDRD model S1 corrected this.  This is a great American made product that just works.  Well done 12oclocklabs!!!
summary: SpeedoDRD S1 Speedometer Calibrator for 2014 DL650A Suzuki Vstrom ABS

Wait 10m in between each coat and run a heat gun at low in between coats and also run the heat gun evenly all over for 1 hour to cure. It will take about 2 to 3 hours to do this but if you take your time and put heat on the shiney spots and keep it all even it will look awesome. More heat= morw wrinkle. There are basically two types of conditioners - water and oil based (be it silicone or other.) The Oil ones tend to live a shine and water-proof your leather. But - some leather will stay "wet", and the leather may transfer the oil to furniture or other clothes.  You learn from experience. I use oil based on my work boots. On the rest of my leather, I prefer water based.

All preservatives/conditioners want you to use a microfiber cloth (or similar.) I'm a guy, and honestly I prefer to squirt the conditioner on my hand and use my palms and fingers to work in the conditioner.  I'm not saying it's the best idea, but I've done it for years. There's also no waste. Anyway, this in non-greasy, with no residue. If you happen to apply too much, a dry cloth will take it right off.  Depending on the leather, this can dry flat or glossy. You can it on an unobtrusive part of your clothing or footwear to see.  It's a preservative and conditioner, not a polish.

On tight-grain leather, like car seats and purser, it will be glossy.  I found that for a pair of man's western boots, it took about two tablespoons of Wild Bill's conditioner per boot. Sometimes my boots will sit in the closet for months - especially the winter wear. I make it a point to treat my boots quarterly, weather or not I've worn them.  I have boots that are 15 years old, and the leather is still supple.

My jackets get treated at least once yearly, usually at the start and end of the season (Winter, fall, etc.)  This product is also great for bike leathers.

reviewText: I got this for my 2011 Honda Pilot. It's better than I expected. The finish on the chrome is not top notch, i.e. some bumps and scratches on it and it's a bit rusted inside of the unit, but that's really not a big deal. From two feet away you don't notice the imperfections in the chrome finish and it looks great. You never see teh rust inside the 2x2 pipe unless you take it out and looks inside it. It's solid and heavy - all metal. And I thought it would be flush with the receptacle once I put in the pin (5/8), but it actually sticks out about one inch from the back of my SUV. I really like that. Gives a bit more protection if anyone should touch your car with their bumper in the parking lot or something. I was even considering getting a real hitch attachement for that purpose (to protect the bumper from small hits), but that would get my pants dirty when I'd putting things in the back. So this thing is perfect - looks great and sticks out a bit, but not as much as to create an inconvenience. NOTE: you need to get a pin separatelly. It takes a 5/8 inch max. (I got Curt Manufacturing 21500 5/8 In Hitch Pin With Clip Polybag W/Upc) but check your car's receptacle hole to make sure you don't need a smaller pin (like a 1/2 inch)/ On Honda Pilot 2011 it's 5/8. Also I put some duct tape around the 2x2 part that goes inside the receptacle (you so you can't see it) to make sure it fits snugly and wouldn't rattle on bumps.

OEM parts are often the best way to go when performing maintenance on your GM car.  And these replacement brake lines for the GMT800 worked very well on my Tahoe to replace it's very rusted originals.  No, they aren't stainless steel like some aftermarket ones you can buy for 3x the price.  And yes, I do wish GM would have used stainless originally so that I wouldn't need to replace them now - 10 years later.  But the original set of brake tubes lasted 10 years, all through Midwest winters, and I I highly doubt the truck will still be around in another 10 years from now, and if so, I'll worry about that in 2025!

Lastly, if you are reading this because your original brake tubes are extremely rusted, I would strongly suggest replacing the fuel lines as well while you're into it.  Both the brake & fuel lines run in parallel next to each other and both suffer from the rust issue.  GM put together this kit at a subsidized price to deal with the brakes, but you still need to deal with the fuel lines too.
summary: OEM parts are often the best way to go when performing maintenance on your GM ...

What can I say, this is my third K&N air filter, this one was installed in my 2011 BMW 335xi. The difference in performance is immediate and somewhat startling. I have no idea how much additional power is being generated, but it's fantastic overall. Low end torque is immediately improved an noticible, no increase in noise or other changes. For those that know BMW's, the 2010 335xi used the N54 twin turbo engine. I owned this vehicle and used KN air filters, it was quite a car. Then I traded it for a 2011 335xi, which uses the N55 "twin power" turbo - note the difference, this engine has only one turbo whereas the N54 has two turbos. There is a definite decrease in torque with the N55, and I was unhappy to say the least. My 2011 BMW had the sport package and nav, though, which is why I upgraded - the seats alone are worth the upgrade. Anyway, after installing this new KN air filter, my 2011 335xi runs with what appears to be at least the same, if not more, power than my former twin-turbo BMW. BMW should include these as standard equipment, for the price, it's a no brainer. Just buy it.
summary: Should be standard equipment on all BMW - immediate power improvement A+

When I received the lock, it looked decent. I tried it on the hitch and it even fit well enough. I then called my wife over to show her how it worked. When I tried to insert the key, I found nothing but an empty hole where the tumbler should be. After a bit of combing, I found it in the leaves and debris on the ground. It seems the retaining pin had backed out, allowing the tumbler to fall out. The retaining pin is supposed to be an interference fit (tight) in the housing. NOT! a very light tap and out it would come, allowing the tumbler to fall out. Well, I fixed that by dimpling around the hole and tapping in the pin.

It then occurred to me how easy it was to dimple with a center punch. Plus, it seemed awfully light in weight. One pass of a hacksaw blade told the story: Cast aluminum! I could cut this off a trailer in less than 5 minutes with any old hacksaw. Come on, at least give us cast iron! Total junk!

Here's the best endorsement I can give for this product I use this on my Bentley Continental Flying Spur. I learned about the product at the Rolls-Royce dealer. You really need a better endorsement than that? If you're not convinced let me explain some extremely basic science behind this For generations people waxed their car using some form of carnauba wax. The reality is the wax does not adhere to the paint and is gone in about three weeks. Now this assumes a few things which includes daily driving, getting your car washed, rain, etc. This product is an amazingly durable polymer which sticks to your paint and really doesn't come off for at least a year. It has a very different type of shine than wax but I believe most enthusiasts will like it just the same.

So what's the downside? This stuff is a real pain to apply and take off. It goes on like butter because it's a liquid but taking it off requires a professional polisher. If you leave it on too long you're going to have a problem. I get my car detailed once a year at the dealership and bring them this instead of the glaze that they normally use. Notice I said glaze and not wax, nobody's using wax anymore it's simply not as effective. To use another analogy 100 years ago people were using a horse-drawn buggy to get from place to place today we have cars. For 50 years or so people used wax to protect their cars paint, today science has given us polymer. Here's the bottom line, the dealership who charges nearly $400,000 for a car uses this product. That convinced me to try for myself and I've been using it faithfully on my cars for the last five years or so. I get more compliments about the appearance of my car now than I ever did using even the fanciest waxes.

One final suggestion, if you're going to attempt to do this yourself you want to start by thoroughly washing your car and making sure that you use a soap that takes off any wax that may still be on the car. Next you have to use a clay bar and lubricant, without this step putting the polymer on it is pointless. As a matter of fact it will damage your paint because you will be ceiling in road grime. Once the car is properly prepped it's time to use very small sections until the car is done. You only need one coat and you will be amazed at the results for at least a year. My strong recommendation is taken to an auto detail company or dealership that you trust and tell them to use this (tell them to follow the instructions on the bottle) instead of whatever they use. You will not regret it. Good luck
summary: Simply the best polymer money can buy simply the best you can buy for your car

Don't buy this to lube a firearm and forget it. Militec 1 is a "system". It's an investment.  I'm not trying to scare anyone away from using this. When applied properly, this is the best treatment for any firearm on the market. I have OCD and have "treated" all my firearms. Once treated, they will operate better than expected by anyone. The short version....clean gun, apply everywhere, heat to around 150-160 degrees, wipe off excess and shoot when you can. I repeat this at least 2 more times. It will make the gun operate better, make it easier to clean and protect it from the elements. After "treating" it, use Militec to clean it also. After I have treated a new gun or a used one I just bought, I actually give that gun a higher value because I know it has changed how the gun operates. If all this sounds silly or stupid, I don't know how else to explain it. My friends and coworkers know exactly how I feel about lubricating my weapons......sorry so long but as you can tell, I AM VERY PASSIONATE ABOUT THIS SUBJECT. if anyone has any questions on how I treat my guns, I am very happy to share the exact procedure that I do.
summary: This is not just a lubricant.....its a "system"

This specific mirror was an OEM option in the 2003-2006 Jeep Wrangler, and my 2006 Wrangler had it from the factory. The lights were a great enhancement to the dome lights behind me, because my head would often block the light from the dome lights behind me (duh!) while these lights were lighting it up from the front. The compass and temperature are always right there visible and are very handy in an offroad vehicle (as you'd imagine).  When I upgraded to a 2012 Wrangler I was shocked to find no auto-dim mirror option available from Chiseler Corporation (intentional mis-spelling of the car company name to describe their habitual behavior). I tried to get along with the stock flip-up mirror but after so many years of the auto-dim mirror it was like going back to horse and buggy days. A Google search uncovered this specific mirror, which is absolutely 100% identical to the mirror that came factory in my old Jeep. Yay!

Only downside: Wiring it up into a vehicle not already wired for it can be tedious. In my case I have a good spot for the temperature sensor and an easy wiring path to get a wire there and a known good source of auxiliary power, and know how to trace wires to e.g. the sport bar dome light back to a point where I can splice into it for these dome lights, but if you're not good with electrical stuff then you'll want to pay an auto electrical shop to do the wiring for you.  So if you have an older 2001-2006 Wrangler without this mirror it's pretty easy to wire up this mirror (the wiring to use it already exists under the plastic panel at the side of the windshield, the temperature sensor wire is even already run to behind the front radiator grill ready for you to plug in the temperature sensor), otherwise be forewarned -- it's not the world's hardest wiring job, but it's non-trivial.

I have a 91 Chevy K2500 with the TH700R4 transmission that was leaking transmission fluid.  It seemed to start leaking after changing the transmission filter and fluid, so I took it for granted that the transmission pan seal was leaking; I changed the seal, but the leak continued.  I got to looking at the transmission more closely and found that the seal to the Throttle Valve (TV) cable was leaking.  I ordered this part from Amazon and replaced it and I no longer have a leak, it was a direct replacement for my truck.  While changing the seal, I also replaced the TV cable.

2.  Pull the cover slowly over the to half of the steering wheel.
3.  Then gradually pull the bottom half on to the steering wheel.

That is it.  Really easy.

reviewText: I already have an OBD code scanner (auto xray) that doesn't read ABS codes. So I bought the Innova to read ABS codes on a 2001 Dodge Grand Caravan.  However, when I plugged it in to the vehicle it told me that the vehicle did not support ABS code protocols.  This is false.  I returned the device (and got my money back promptly - thanks Amazon).  I then bought the actron ABS code reader which DID read the ABS code for 1/4th the innova price.  I don't know how well the Innova does with OBD codes, but it fails the test when it comes to reading ABS codes.  Bottom line is that the Innova does NOT read ABS codes for all 1996 and forward Chrysler products.  Considering that the Caravan and Grand Caravan are some of the largest selling Dodge vehicles, I find it inexcusable that a device that claims to read most '96 and onward GM Ford and Chrysler vehicle ABS codes failed to read a 2001 Dodge Grand Caravan.

If there was anyone hesitating to get this product, don't hesitate and get it.  It's pretty compact and fits into any cupholder.  It has an on/off switch so that you don't have to plug/unplug the unit just to turn it on or off.  There is a fan that makes noise when you turn it on.  This is a good indicator to let you know that your unit is on and its working.  Also, this was meant to be used when your car is on. Anyway, I was able to use this to charge a 13" Macbook (which only required 65W) and simultaneously charge a USB device as well.  There are multiple USB charging slots available but just know that the USB chargers all draw from the same power so if you plug in two or three devices the charging will be split between them which means they won't charge as fast. This mirror is identical in shape to the OEM glass.  The generic instructions say to use the urethane tape (4 sq inches total supplied) and just stick it on the broken mirror.

Not a good long term fix.  Completely removing the old glass with screw drivers and a sharp putty knife gives a better install.

The OEM glass is only held to the backing by 4 to 6 sq inches of mastic tape, so the supplied tape is almost enough.  I added 6 large pea sized globs of Blackjack, a roof sealant that is widely available in a caulk tube and sticks to everything.  Professional glass installer urethane adhesive would be better, but it is 20 dollars a tube vs 2 bucks for blackjack.

I placed the supplied tale on the raised pads on the glass holder, and applied the blackjack around the edges of the backing.  Pressed the glass into place, making sure it stuck to the tape, and used the foam envelope that shipped with the glass to press so as to spread the pressure.

Done this way, the mirror sits in the support frame instead of standing proud as it would do if just stuck on the remaining broken glass.

Eye protection is a must while working with any glass, esp removing the old, broken mirror.
summary: Works well, but install a bit involved

reviewText: This is my 6th HID kit 2nd from Innovited.  I am very familiar with installation and it typically takes me all of 5 minutes to install and this was set up like any other Bi-Xenon kit, however my first issue was the bulbs had to be forced into the light housing as they are pretty oversized.  Probable cause being the fact they are Bi-Xenon and that requires a mechanism to move the bulb forward and back for Hi-Low beams.  However, that makes it difficult to install the bulbs in the case of the 9007 because of the tube it has to be jammed into is now too small for the bulb.  However that was over come after 10 or 15 minutes of trying to force it in.  The next problem arrived when I went to test the kit.  I switched on my Rangers headlights.  The familiar whine/hum of the ballasts kicked in and the familiar strengthening glow filled my garage.  After allowing the bulbs to reach full strength (which notably did not take long) I flicked the bulbs up to High beam... and nothing happened.  I tried twice more despite Einstein's definition of insanity.  This was not the first time I have had this problem with a new set of Bi-Xenon. The problem stems from the relay being incorrectly wired where it plugs into the cars light socket.  Because I already understood the problem I chose not to call customer service so I can not attest to customer service only to their product quality control.  After a few minutes I was able to determine the correct order of the wires and I now have the kit functioning.  I am underwhelmed with what the high-beams look like.  I will probably be replacing the bulbs with some from another company at some point in the future.  Still not a bad deal for the money and just the low-beam is much better than the stock lights.  Not sure if I would buy another kit from Innovited although the kit I put in my wife's car is nice (also Bi-Xenon just a different size).  Unless the 55w is something you really want I would look at Kensun.
summary: Affordable, and solidly built....  had some issues though

I have a manual so there are some quirks with it. One of which is the fact of course that it comes in manual mode where you have to shut the car down in a certain way in order to be able to remote start it. The only downfall is that once you actually open, not unlock, the doors, the sequence is broken and you have to jump in and reset the sequence. Engine on, car in gear, car in neutral, with foot on brake set the e-brake, on the remote hit the lock button, remove key exit car, hit the lock button. It's quite annoying but I've managed to find sort of a workaround. If you need to get back in your car, just remote start it, then unlock it go in do what you need to do, then close the doors and s*** off the remote start. sequence is still in tact and you get to open the doors. As everyone say that one mile range is like in a perfectly clear line of site. Sometimes I can't hit my car from less that a tenth of a mile away because there is a row of houses in between. Another weird thing that happens is that sometimes I'll try to start , it will say out of range, then I'll try again and it will say "deactivated" meaning the first time actually worked. In addition, I'll be able to hit the unlock and lock buttons, but not moving from the same spot, have the remote start say out of range. As for the buttons, they do press incredibly easily and you can very well lock/unlock/start your car without knowing. My solution was to use the auto button lock that they provide as a feature, but that also leads to some slight issues where you can remote start your car by accident if the buttons are already unlocked. The combination of buttons to unlock the buttons are the remote start, then unlock. That unlocks the buttons, but if your buttons are already unlocked, you just started and unlocked your car. My solution to this was to always roll the jog wheel first to check. If the keys are unlocked it will go into the features menu, if not it will let you know immediately that the keys are locked. I also purchased this case Black Leather Case for Viper 7944V Remote Systems since there is no real screen protector for this and I'd rather not have to buy another remote for an accidental drop or scratched screen from my keys. The case definitely adds some bulk though. The LED screen is beautiful, it kills the battery a little but the remote is usb rechargeable so that's not a problem. Also, the tones were annoying to me so I turned off the action tones and only have the buttons tones on. Then I realized that I would never know if someone was actually breaking into my car so I turned on the vibration. I haven't added any other sensors to it as yet since I was on a budget and really just wanted a starter but I'm looking forward to trying some of the other sensors. I'm sure there are features that I left out, but I hope this helps

I was very pleased with this hitch. I needed to put a Thule T2 bike rack on the car, both are roughly 30lb full suspension mountain bikes and the bike rack weighs 50lb. The installation was quite easy to my surprise. I did it myself, I had to get creative and let one side lay on my leg while I got the bolts in on one side. Once I got all sides started I used a torque wrench to make sure they were tightened to specifications. I'd strongly recommend using the torque wrench. I didn't have one initially, I did my best to crank it down with a regular socket wrench. It felt "good enough" but I decided to run to the hardware store and buy an 18 inch torque wrench. I was surprised when I realized how loose it still was, once I got it torqued to spec it was solid. I stood on the hitch and bounced to check it out. I luckily didn't have any issues with the rack being bent during shipping like others have said.

Once more note, I bought this for a 2013 Rav4. While it fits perfectly, anything you're towing is going to have little ground clearance. Its not the hitch's fault, the Rav4 just doesnt have a lot of clearance. Our bike rack has hit the ground on steep driveways, not the outer part of the rack but the part thats sticking out from the hitch. I measured the ground clearance for our rack at the hitch point and it was only 8 inches. Granted, the car was loaded with camping gear, the bikes/rack weight but even unloaded we only had 9.5 inches.
summary: A sturdy hitch with easy installation.

Good battery charger that tries to do the least damage to the battery when charging while also trying to post the least risk of fire hazard. Most battery chargers can be annoying, especially these smart chargers but they do what they do mostly to protect the user and the battery. Most batteries have issues with charging because the voltage is too low and or you choose too fast of a charge rate. Charging severely discharged batteries is difficult whether it be a smart or a dumb charger.

Here is the procedure for charging 12v batteries that are very discharged with a standing voltage of less than 9V. First you attach the battery charger to the dead battery. Then, with some jumper cables, attach a mostly charged battery (around 12v) to the dead battery in parallel using the jumper cables (Positive to Positive, Negative to Negative). The charger should detect a voltage of 12v, then charge at the lowest rate (2 amps) with this configuration for at least 3 hours. After 3 hours, you should be able to disconnect the "good" (charged) battery and be able to continue charging the "bad" (discharged) battery at the lowest charge rate. If you're desperate to get things up and running ASAP, wait until the battery is charged up to 11.8V then if you want, you can choose a higher charge rate. Don't choose a fast charge rate when bringing a severely discharged battery up to 11v otherwise you'll receive error codes.

Error codes are very common and you pretty much have to play around with it until it begins to charge.

Battery chargers don't allow for charging of severely discharged batteries as a precaution because they don't want people charging 6V batteries accidentally or creating sparks by having it output 10a of electricity when there isn't anything hooked up. I've successfully charged about 15 car batteries with about 8 of them below 3V, some as low as 0V with this method. These chargers work great, it's just that you have to understand how they work in order to get them to do what you want.
summary: These chargers are good but have some caveats

You must remove the heavy rust. For me, this is more like a step in a multi-step process of rust removal, prep and paint.

Every vehicle is different.  Different electronics.  Different lamp reflectors.  This may work in one car, and not another.  Simple problems like hyper-flashing are easy to fix.  I've heard of all kinds of issues from simple "plug & play" installations.  People have reported that their cruise control unit failed after installing a LED lamp.

When I installed LED lamps on my car, the obvious problem occurred. "Hyper-Blinking". All lamps turned on, and flashed extremely fast.

My next solution was to use a LED Decoder 3157a Adapter, also sourced from Amazon. "Hyper-Blinking" was solved. But now, there were other issues. I signal left, or signal right, all lights would flash like hazard lights. My dash lights would go on, and my odometer would dim, with each flicker and flash. If I applied the brakes, the front signal lights would burn steady like the rear brake lights. If my headlamps were turned on, then signaling, braking, and turning on the hazard light switch would only turn the lamps on to high, and stay on as if brakes were being applied, without any flashing.

On my car, the solution was a Tridon EP27 flasher relay.

I installed this unit into the tail lights for brakes and reverse, and the front signal lamp.  In the tail lamp, the white light behind the red lens works just fine.  The reverse lights are brighter, way brighter, than the OEM lamps.  The OEM front signal lamp is a yellow light bulb, which also doubles as a parking lamp.  Be sure that you are not violating any local ordinances prior to installation.  Your local jurisdiction may not be happy with a white light facing forward and flashing.  Your local constable may issue a citation for modifying your vehicle with lights that did not come from the manufacturer.

Amazon was perfect shipping this to me etc. etc.  They always have done right by me.  However...

As far is this part is concerned I would go with the OEM part even if it is a little more expensive.  If you don't care about your vehicle that much and you just want a quick, cheap fix this will work for you.
I purchased this for my 2001 Jeep Cherokee Sport
Here are my issues with this part:
1) The metal base that gets bolted to the vehicle is not coated in any way.  This will start to rust immediately.  The OEM part has a nice black epoxy finish.  The reason you are replacing the old one in the first place is because it most likely was rusted.
2) The bolts that protrude through from the bottom are two mild steel bolts that have two tack welds holding them in place.  The problem with using the threw bolts like that is that it will never sit flush up against the 'frame' where it attaches.  This means water will sit up there, rust the part, and the frame.  The OEM part uses studs that have been recessed into the metal part and are completely flush with the back side.  In all the places I researched the Walker part you never see the tops of those bolts in the pictures (pretty sneaky).
3) This part comes dissembled.  The OEM part comes assembled.

I hope this helps the next person make the correct choice. There are lots of places to buy Mopar parts online, I would start there you can get the part number from any parts place or your service manual.  I'm all for saving money on parts but this one is IMHO inferior to the OEM part.
summary: Buy the OEM part if you care about your vehicle.

For even greater air flow control, the hose cuff on the blower end screws off in a clockwise direction and screws back on in a counter clockwise direction.

David Stern

I had been thinking of different ways that I might attach some type of trailer hitch to the back of my Kubota B2320 tractor.  I was searching Amazon for what I hoped might help me adapt a standard tow bar to my tractor and came across this item which is exactly what I needed. The product appears to be well built and is a great value for the price!  I have two trailers (one with 1-7/8' ball and one with 2' ball) and was pleased to be able to move either one without having to change the tow bar.  Having this on the 3 point hitch also allowed me to "disconnect" from one trailer and "connect" to another without having to adjust the tongue jacks on the trailers; just lower, back under and raise.  This item is perfect for what I need to do!

ONE WORD OF CAUTION:  Be sure this item is level and "locked in" with the 3 Point hitch linkage so that it cannot move or rotate during use.  I neglected to do this the first use and bent my trailer coupler because the tow bar was able to sway and rotate in the 3 point hitch.

ONE LAST CAUTION:  After a few uses, I noticed the hitch balls had come loose; evidently not tightened sufficiently when the item was assembled.  No bit deal to tighten but keep and eye out to be sure yours have not become loose!

reviewText:
Installed on my 2015 grizzly 700 EPS SE. has plenty of torque, enough to drag my 4 wheeler up a sand hill in the creek with the brakes locked effortlessly. the motor is nice and quiet and can barely hear it over the stock exhaust.  the synthetic rope is great, but keep in mind it has to be cared for and cleaned. Wrapping it tight on the drum will keep the rope from burying itself when its put under a load. Just tie off to a truck and have a buddy lightly brake while you guide the rope on the spool.  Either way its better than cable IMO despite not being as abrasion resistant.  I highly recommend the Factor55 Prolink XTV. It is a way better option for recovery than the plain hook.

The supplied 6 gauge wire was more than enough to run to the very back, if your 4 wheeler has a battery installed at the rear.  on the Grizzly, the battery is under the front rack, so i had to cut 6 feet off every cable and crimp/solder new terminals to make a nice clean install. speaking of wiring its very simple and the solenoid and winch is color coated for which wire goes where.

Pros: powerful motor, steel drum for synthetic rope, plenty of cable for installation, Quiet operation.

Cons: Circuit breaker is not the best for mounting. its all exposed 12V on the body so you have to isolate it from coming in contact with metal.  large heat shrink in a few layers will solve this problem. but i feel they could have supplied one with a plastic body instead.  oh well, its an easy problem to fix.

reviewText: I bought these from VML via Amazon and my set arrived with some metal scoring where the mounting plate attches to the light with the supplied screw. This is a very nice, easy-to-use, affordable wireless Portable Digital Tire Pressure Gauge from LotFancy that provided accurate reading tonight on all three of our cars. I would recommend this unit if you are looking to purchase such a device.

Simple to use:

* Take it out of the retail package
* Push the button once if you need a light blue light to help find the valve stem
* Seat the opening securely on the top of the valve and push the button
* Read the result
* Done

Not a moments problem using this pressure gauge. The information in the Amazon listing describes the light as a "bright LED flashlight" which is not accurate -- it emits a light, blue wash of light that helps you find the valve stem when it is really dark outside.

The backlit LCD readout is very nice to have and very easy to read, and the single button operation could not be easier. The handgrip is very comfortable to hold and use... somebody put a lot of thought into the design, and it shows, and it is delivered ready to run with batteries already installed.

No warranty information in the Amazon listing or retail documentation, so if an issue occurs in a reasonable period of time I would return here to update the review and let you know what the issue was and how resolution was handled. I did receive this digital tire pressure gauge gratis from the seller and have put to use to objectively find out how well it performed. My statements here reflect that testing.

This Portable Digital Tire Pressure Gauge from LotFancy greatly exceeded our expectations. If you are looking for a tire pressure gauge of this price, size and style, for use similar to what I have described above, then we would absolutely recommend giving this one a try based on our experience with it.

Very recommended.

Go for it.

These are very bright and easy to install but there is definitely a cross-hatched pattern of lighter (whiter) and darker (yellowish) light emitted from these fixtures. It is much more evident when illuminating a solid white object than anything else. If those who haven't noticed it would hold up a sheet of white paper anywhere the light shines I'd almost guarantee they'd see it clearly. We have several white surfaces in our camper where I installed three of these and the projected patterns was very annoying. The yellowish bands are about the same color as white plastic after it has aged, so not only is the pattern itself distracting, whatever it's shining on looked old and dreary too. So I was in a quandary trying to decide if the much brighter output, lower power consumption and heat was worth enduring, and hopefully getting accustomed to the banding. I decided to try to figure out the source of the pattern, presuming at first that it was the small cross-hatch pattern molded into the lens cap. Some testing by holding up a white nylon cutting board while covering various portions of the lens though, proved this not to be the case. It is actually being cause by the arrangement of the individual LED elements as their light passes through the clear focusing lens in the center of the lens cap. This focusing lens is presumably there to direct light downward onto anything directly below it, and would probably work perfectly well with a single bulb, but with an array of LEDs it creates an effect that was surely unanticipated and for many, I'm sure, will be unwelcome. Thankfully, once I understood the problem, with a little experimenting I found a solution that was very acceptable for me. All I did was cut a paper towel the size of the oval focusing lens and then separated the plies of the paper and put a single ply between the LED array and the lens cap. This serves as a suitable defuser and the lines are completely eliminated without appreciably decreasing the light output. The LEDs run super cool so I can't believe there could be a heat issue with this solution but I'll be checking it later to make sure and would recommend you do the same if you decide to try it. I may try to come up with something else besides paper to serve as the defuser as I guess there are a lot of translucent materials that would work as well. Just a frosted sheet of plastic would probably be ideal. Anyway, I hope this helps for others who have experienced this and would like a cheap, easy fix.

I got this for a 2011 Honda Accord's driver side window since it was described as like OEM and was suppose to fit the car.  Unfortunately, they don't fit work/fit well at all.  As other 2011 Accord owners may know, the wiper arm is a unique design that can be very picky on which wiper frame designs will actually work and provide a clean wipe.  I was hoping that these "OEM" based wipers would do the job since they certainly do look like the OEM.  But the biggest issue with these is that they don't wipe the windshield fully.  They leave a small arc about 4 inches wide and 7 inches long untouched in the middle of the windshield.

Even had these wipers provided a good full-contact wipe, I don't think they would have lasted very long as the frame was made from very frail-feeling plastics.  And for some reason, they glued the rubber wiper onto the wiper frame.  I think it's another cheap short cut they took since all other wiper frames generally use a mechanical attachment system that allows you to replace the rubber squeegee portion.

I bought this so I could hook it to the quick disconnect on my Sunforce 50022 5-watt solar battery trickle charger for our generator.  I wanted to have the ring terminals to hook onto my 12 volt generator battery rather than having to use the alligator clips that came with the Solar panel.  I wanted to be sure it was charging, so decided to check it out with my voltmeter.  I read minus (negative) volts.  Then I read a review someone did on the solar battery trickle charger that warned the Battery Tender 2-pin quick disconnect was wired wrong to work with this solar charger, even though it is listed as an item that is recommended to buy with the solar charger.  The solar charger has a negative male on the disconnect plug, so it needs a negative female on the Battery Tender to plug into.  However, the Battery Tender 2-pin quick disconnect plug is wired up with a positive female, so instead of charging the battery when they are connected, it actually drains it.  We took this Battery Tender quick disconnect off our generator battery and instead used the alligators clips that came with the solar panel trickle charger, and it is charging perfectly now.  I gave it a one star because it did not work with the item it was recommended for.
summary: Do NOT use with Sunforce 5-watt battery trickle charger

reviewText:
"Fixing a hydraulic clutch slave cylinder in a 2007 Wrangler" I did an install video online under that title.
I LOST MY CLUTCH.. AGAIN!  Different Jeep though. There is that monument when you start the jeep and it just takes off, it was an indication of a problem. The clutch had very little action and that only near the floor. As I left and headed out in 5 oclock traffic I soon discovered that shifting and stopping were going to be an issue. I drove home in 3rd gear slowing to avoid a stop and stall. Under the transmission bell at the seam there was some fluid dripping. This was my second clue.  Here is the list of tools and part numbers to get the repair done.

Pros:
Quick shipping.
Perfect fit.
Easy to bleed.
All parts included.

Cons:
It needs a zip tie thing that snaps off after inserted like on a YJ.
Getting it to compress and line up is hard if pre-bled.

Tools needed:
13 MM deep socket
6 inch extension
Ratchet
Small flathead.
DOT3 fluid.
Drip pan. Place pan under cylinder to catch fluid.

Step one:
Remove two nuts holding clutch cylinder to transmission. Unhook any cables in the way.

Step two.
Use small flat head to remove retaining clip on top where line connects.
Twist and pull, watch out to make sure rubber fitting is not damaged, you may need that.

Step three.
Attach new cylinder and secure with hairpin clip. The line needs to be pushed completely in or it will pop out.

Step four.
Bleed cylinder by pushing plunger in slowly till you cant hear air bubbles passing through to reservoir. This took around 15 times for me. MAKE SURE YOU HAVE FLUID IN THE RESERVOIR.

Step five.
Make sure plunger is properly aligned and push towards mounting bolts. Check to see if line bracket is lined up with holes on side of cylinder.

Step six.
Tighten bolts and secure all disconnected components.

Step seven.
Bleed cylinder as needed. If needed have someone push the clutch in as you open the valve to let any air bubbles out.  Just like brakes.

Check to see if clutch is properly working and no grinding occurs when shifting.  If all goes well there should be no fluid on the lower portion of the transmission bell and you should be good to go.
summary: Fixing a clutch slave cylinder in a 2007 Wrangler

reviewText:
First off, i never tried it w/ both hoses, i disconnected the second line and only ran a single line to the container.

Also - you need to get the correct size connector for your air compressor.  I used a small compressor and the 1/4" connector.  That and some teflon tape had me up and running in just a few minutes.

Hooked up to a small 1.5hp air compressor (i think maxes out around 90psi) - what i use for airing up tires.

Almost worked too well!  I nearly ran my small reservoir dry a couple times (on 3 motorcycles).  Takes a bit of getting used to the flow rate of the vacuum and is easy to run the reservoir dry.  Rate of suction and flow rate are adjusted by how much you squeeze the handle - just some fine tuning and getting used to it.

Compared w/ my Mityvac MV8000 - it's far easier.  (it does require an air compressor though).  Also i like the quality flexible (Silicone?) hoses that came with this unit WAY BETTER than the hard lines of the mityvac!!

If i were to nit-pick a little, i think the overall unit is well made.  A gauge would be helpful to give me a measurement to target vacuum (which equals flow rate) so i don't over-draw and run the reservoir dry.  Small gripe, and honestly i just needed a helper or to stop and top off more frequently.  It's hard to complain about it being too easy and fast... but that's pretty much the only negative.

I looked at the Mityvac vacuum ($$$ air compressor assisted) units.  This unit (only being about the same price as the MV8000 (also the cheapest mityvac "kit") which i have already), and the better quality hoses - this is hands down a better option.  And if it fails in a year i'd still have to buy several before it cost as much as the assisted vacuum Mityvac ones.

Highly recommend.
summary: Almost too good - need a larger reservoir!
